Sorry, River!<br>
<br>
Basically, our take on it is basically this: Run your raid, but it's open to Alliance members first and foremost (subject to your normal raid rules ... a lot of people have potential guild members on raids). Your same loot rules are in effect and are extended to Alliance members present. You're still in charge. If this is a raid, say, to get a VS drop for four designated guild members, there's no need to roll on those loots if they drop.<br>
<br>
You get more bodies and perhaps access to classes that are under-represented in your crew. The people coming along get to see and do things with the same group of people over and over, even if they couldn't necessarily do it with their own guilds solo. They also get a reasonable chance at loot and learn more about the game.<br>
<br>
We ran a long, if abortive, raid on Sky (which is how it can be long AND abortive) recently that was open to the Alliance to get a guild ranger an epic drop. There was death, people having to leave as key supplies weren't as plentiful as they might have been if we were all more seasoned in Sky, and I'm not sure if anyone got any real loot out of the deal. Still, everyone seemed to have a good time.<br>
<br>
Likewise, last week we ran an open KD raid, although we capped the number of people who could attend. We had several drops go to non-Walkers, and it was a rewarding and fun experience for all involved. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ukaguera.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kaguera </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/1/01 10:47:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=61.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Vazaelle Alliance</span><hr size=1> Mate,<br>
<br>
I think all have experienced the problem of members leaving to join uber guilds. It is part of the game. It can be difficult because once players reach that 50 level (especially clerics and enchanter) they are in big demand. After being invited to attend a couple of plane raids and getting the items that most of classes in uber guilds already have, some will look at their guild in a different light. Some will start to wonder why their guild can't get there butt in gear and get this same stuff, not realizing that getting the numbers and appropriate classes takes time and dedication. The good news is that those that stay and stick it out will be true gems to your guild. <br>
<br>
I know that it took some time but UCOV is finally seeing some of our long-term goals come to fruition. The Alliance (Razor's Edge, Walkers, Avatar's of the Rising Pheonix, Wardens, Lucid Chimera, Unbroken Circle of Valor) was the best thing that ever happened to our guild. We are able to retain our uniqueness and also allow our dedicated members to enjoy all aspects of Norrath. I recommend that all mid-sized guilds willing to stick it out should try to attain allies with the similar<br>
values and goals.<br>
<br>
Our motto has always been:<br>
<br>
We value our UCOV Community above anything else. Nurturing this, all else will come in good time, but it will be done together.<br>
<br>
Good Luck Mate<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
